(Import [(hv5f ([(Technology (Software (Engineering Architecture)))] Principle [When the existing shape does not fit, follow where the logic wants to go rather than being bound by what is already there — let the water find where it wants to go downhill. Desire paths name this: the trail walked into the grass because that is how the body naturally moves, regardless of where the paved walkway was put. Architecture grows the same way, and where multiple agents independently arrive at the same shape, that convergence is the signal it is the right shape.] High Minimum Zero [desire-paths architecture-convergence])) (t5wx ([(Technology (Software (Engineering Architecture))) (Technology (Software (Programming Compilation)))] Decision [|The schema-codegen capability set is closed and covers the engine's structural needs (types, generic frame expansion, payload structs/newtypes/enums, standard impls, role/marker traits, shape-computed constants, method-bearing trait surface, actor wiring, plane carriers, opt-in Deref). The next phase is integration and migration, not language design: flip scalar-newtype impls default-on, integrate onto code-repo main, and PORT all components — regenerate spirit, signal-spirit, meta-signal-spirit and the triad through the emitter, swapping generated Rust in for hand-wired boilerplate; only abstract engine bodies (decide, validate) stay hand-written. Each plane is defined in schema, assembled into Asschema, emitted as Rust datatypes and basic trait impls, with hand-written Rust the decision-making actor system over schema-emitted nouns. Spirit must be a proper contract-daemon/engine-stack exemplar, not an all-in-one non-copyable pilot. Shipped runtime binaries stay small carrying only strict rkyv wire/storage contracts; the schema/NOTA compiler (nota-next, schema-next, schema-rust-next) is build-time-only and never links into the runtime binary, and the NOTA text codec is an optional edge feature absent from the daemon.|] High Medium Zero [schema-next schema-rust-next spirit signal-spirit triad-runtime rkyv])) (ctkv ([(Technology (Software (Engineering Architecture)))] Decision [|persona-spirit is the production Spirit component (its own repo, currently the only component in production); the repo named spirit (formerly spirit-next) is the next-generation schema-derived Spirit — the active schema-derived implementation should carry the spirit name, since the separate spirit-next repo only arose from the psyche referring to the next Spirit. Future Spirit expansion uses spirit-next as design inspiration while tying together the richer data in production Spirit. Schema work has its own repo named schema. The -next replacement repos have won: nota-next is the canonical NOTA and schema-next + schema-rust-next the canonical schema stack, deprecating the old nota/schema repos; the now-vestigial -next suffix should be dropped, renaming replacements to base names.|] High Minimum Zero [spirit persona-spirit spirit-next nota-next schema-next])) (57f9 ([(Technology (Software (Engineering Architecture))) (Technology (Software (Distributed ProtocolDesign)))] Decision [|Router owns a standardized routing protocol: a router-typed envelope carries routing/object metadata for a serialized contract-owned rkyv payload while Router stays payload-blind beyond envelope/routing/authentication/delivery policy, and is the sole operational subscription matcher for non-direct message passing. Object-update fan-out is owned by subscribing components and Router, not by criome computing per-object impact: criome stamps/authorizes the object and emits an authorized-object reference (not payload); Router matches subscriptions and fans references to subscribers, who fetch the referenced rkyv object. Accepted objects are quorum-backed by default, not single-node signed. Time-driven pulses are not an ambient heartbeat: an after-time contract schedules a later check that, if its events did not occur, triggers a new quorum-signed acceptance. The first production milestone is the spirit -> criome -> router -> mirror chain: Spirit asks local criome to authenticate a content-addressed object, criome verifies/signs it under a cluster-root identity and propagates via Router; the remote mirror fetches/restores object state — criome auth-only, Router transport-only, mirror the version-control substrate. Mirror topology is per-system (one mirror per node, symmetric with the per-system router); the receiving mirror owns fetch/restore after the authenticated head notice. The mirror is the psyche's cross-machine self: editing on any owner machine propagates as a criome-authorized state transition, with criome authority on the latest approved head and Spirit fetching it rather than deciding locally. The mirror aspect may fold into the Spirit daemon.|] High Minimum Zero [router criome mirror spirit])) (pviw ([(Technology (Software (Engineering Architecture))) (Technology (Software (Security Authorization))) (Technology (Software (Distributed ProtocolDesign)))] Decision [|Telos is the umbrella name for the whole meta-project, from Greek telos (ultimate end), whose far horizon is eventual Criome and eventual Sema, realized now as Persona, the meta-AI of language models over typed dumb mechanism. criome is Telos's agreement-and-authorization organ — a universal agreement machine for authorization — not Telos itself. The quorum is criome's universal primitive: one quorum primitive scoped by membership serves both reliability/credible-time (a principal's own multiple nodes) and cross-party trust (multiple principals). criome's internal language is a limited typed policy language over public-key identity atoms (not a general VM; discipline drawn from Ethereum/Tezos/Solana VMs), composing identity contracts from k-of-n signature quorums and time-locks with time-varying thresholds, plus explicit divergence-reconciliation objects (conflict resolution may invoke an LLM-oracle). Verdicts come from gathered BLS quorum signatures, from a connected approver over criome's meta socket (mentci is that client), or from a configured auto-approve policy (bootstrap/testing); contracts can escalate to a named adjudicator (mechanical quorum, LLM panel, smarter agent, or the psyche) whose signed content-addressed verdict criome only verifies. Verdicts are closed typed outcomes over already-submitted objects (approve/reject/defer/non-judge/escalate), never carriers of new content; non-judgment is first-class and the default LLM judge leans toward abstaining and escalating, the psyche being highest-authority lowest-availability (EscalateToPsyche is an inert dead-letter until the psyche UI exists). criome may run as multiple deployment instances (system criome and home/user criome) — same two contracts, differing by privilege tier. The Criome domain component is domain-criome and excludes provider APIs and direct CLI store access. signal-standard is a new shared schema for genuine cross-component standards — first the ComponentKind roster + differentiator (closed-but-partitioned), then standard typed connection points (Unix socket path, optional port); it is the second shared signal- library alongside signal-frame.|] Medium Medium Zero [criome telos persona domain-criome mentci signal-standard quorum])) (ay3y ([(Technology (Software (Distributed ProtocolDesign))) (Technology (Software (Security Authentication)))] Decision [|criome's clock is decentralized quorum-attested coarse crystallized-PAST time, not a single trusted or precise clock. A time attestation begins as a forward-extending window proposition (content-addressed as its identity); a quorum signs that the present falls within the window, closing it at last signature or expiry, crystallizing a non-forgeable monotonic lower bound on now (only the past is provable). The window extends forward so every member can sign; the tolerance gap is bounded below by quorum signing latency, widening under partition. Every quorum-signed object carries an attested moment (a signature is never timeless), so every admission envelope, verdict, agreement fact, and triad input/output is time-bound for freshness/replay reasoning; time-locks compare against the operation's own proof-of-when. AttestedMoment is the self-grounding base case carrying no inner moment, stopping the regress.|] Medium Minimum Zero [criome attested-moment crystallized-time quorum])) (lt44 ([(Technology (Software (Engineering Architecture))) (Technology (Software (Distributed ProtocolDesign)))] Decision [|CriomOS communication has two transport lanes: Router is the ordinary fabric for cross-sandbox/cross-network traffic (router-to-router remote delivery, reference push, payload-blind byte movement), and criome has a direct criome-to-criome peer lane for time-sensitive agreement (quorum signing, crystallized-time windows) carrying only agreement/authorization messages — keeping criome auth-only and Router general transport. Each agent runs in its own microVM sandbox; the tailnet gives confidentiality and criome BLS attestations per-frame authenticity; intra-host sandbox-to-router transport is tap/L3 (vsock deferred for losing SO_PEERCRED). Mirror version-controls and moves objects.|] Medium Minimum Zero [criomos router criome mirror microvm])) (g31j ([(Technology (Software (Engineering Architecture)))] Clarification [|Component binary naming: each component (role name, e.g. persona, spirit, harness, orchestrator) has a CLI half <component> and a daemon half <component>-daemon — the role name is not itself a binary. Persona is composed of binary 'persona' (thin CLI) and 'persona-daemon' (long-lived daemon); converge older phrasings ('persona engine', 'engine-manager daemon') to 'Persona'. Persona disambiguation suffixes only when wrapping (persona-codex, persona-pi, persona-claude). In the running-orchestrated-system goal, Orchestrate is the orchestrate COMPONENT (repo /git/github.com/LiGoldragon/orchestrate), the runtime that runs the set of component daemons (persona the supervisor, the introspector, the schema daemon, others) — not the act of orchestrating.|] High Minimum Zero [persona orchestrate component-naming persona-daemon])) (edgt ([(Technology (Software (Engineering Architecture)))] Decision [persona-prefix retirement and owner->core terminology: persona-spirit becomes spirit, signal-persona-spirit becomes signal-spirit, owner-signal-persona-spirit becomes core-signal-spirit; the pattern drops the persona prefix where not needed and moves owner terminology to core terminology because core is the privileged control/library layer while signal-* stays the ordinary messaging layer for safer callers/extensions. signal-persona-auth renames to signal-persona-origin.] High Minimum Zero [spirit signal-spirit core-signal-spirit signal-persona-origin])) (gdbf ([(Technology (Software (Engineering Architecture)))] Decision [|The agent component is a new abstraction over harness backends — persona-claude/codex/gemini/pi/open-code are its backends — built as an LLM-API-call component making provider HTTP API calls in API style, not an agent-harness front door (harness backends deferred); Router talks to the agent component, not harness directly. DeepSeek-as-library folds into the persona-pi triad (no separate deepseek component). Persona Pi is a real persona-component triad (daemon + signal-persona-pi + meta/owner-signal-persona-pi + thin pi CLI), running inside a terminal-cell for Unix I/O but also talking directly to the harness API (the more accessible logic surface). Mencie, the persona multi-modal UI, is implemented as nexus schemas, one per UI panel.|] Medium Medium Zero [agent persona-pi harness mencie nexus])) (hqg7 ([(Technology (Software (Engineering Architecture)))] Correction [Harness production shape should be one component daemon owning multiple harness instances internally; one OS daemon per harness is too heavy for the intended design. Per-harness boundaries live as records/actors/adapters inside the harness daemon, not as separate component processes.] Medium Minimum Zero [harness])) (7x5z ([(Technology (Software (Engineering Architecture))) (Technology (Software (Surfaces CommandLineInterfaces)))] Decision [|mentci is a first-class component triad and a state-bearing programmable user-interface daemon owning canonical interface state (UI changes because daemon state changed); TUI, CLI, editor, status-bar, popup, email, and agentic clients subscribe and send updates back. It interacts heavily with the local criome for question/approval flows and key decrypt/use (criome owns the key store). Shape: mentci daemon repo (daemon + thin CLI + daemon-local signal/nexus/sema runtime schemas) plus signal-mentci and meta-signal-mentci wire contracts; mentci-lib is the shared app/state-machine library reused by daemon and clients, and mentci-egui is one thin client.|] Medium Minimum Zero [mentci criome mentci-lib mentci-egui])) (rxcp ([(Technology (Software (Engineering Architecture)))] Decision [|Horizon splits into RAW horizon — the core typed cluster-data model (NodeService enum, typed facts, arch resolution, name/key-line newtypes, cross-node fan-in, typed validation, secret-binding resolution) — and a separate PRETTY horizon layer that computes in typed Rust (not Nix) the pre-derived variables Nix consumes (behaves-as/gating booleans, resolved magnitudes, lid-switch policy, trust-gated extra-groups); Nix only uses already-derived variables. This split is also a forward-integration seam: keeping raw horizon clean and minimal keeps the door open to promote it into a real component later, while pretty stays the typed derive layer. The split applies ONLY to the new lojix/horizon-next stack; production Stack A horizon stays as-is until cutover. Rationale: spend the cleanliness budget on the durable layer that outlives the bootstrap substrate (Nix, which the future Forge replaces) and let unavoidable glue ugliness live in the throwaway substrate.|] Medium Medium Zero [horizon lojix nix forge])) (1hyg ([(Technology (Software (Engineering Architecture))) (Technology (Software (Operations ConfigurationManagement)))] Decision [|The LojixOS split is a rename-and-configuration split: the generic OS substrate becomes LojixOS while CriomOS becomes a simple per-deploy configuration crate holding a thin NOTA data tree that lojix precompiles into binary config. Cloud-node OS images live in CriomOS as a minimal CloudNode-species profile, declaratively built with an image builder (not by snapshotting a converted running droplet) and content-sized so a node boots fast on the smallest sensible droplet (multi-tens-of-GB is unacceptable). Per-node configuration is declared in the cluster data (the horizon cluster proposal). The cloud daemon references the image by id through HostPlan image_name and never holds the image definition; CriomOS owns the image definition and provider-format build, cloud owns snapshot-id selection and provisioning.|] Medium Minimum Zero [lojix criomos cloud horizon])) (150a ([(Technology (Software (Engineering Architecture)))] Decision [|The cloud component's next active capability is on-demand compute-node provisioning via cloud-hoster provider APIs, beyond the shipped Cloudflare read-only DNS path, targeting easiest-to-spin-up providers first. DigitalOcean is the lead compute provider (superseding Hetzner-lead): primary provisioning target, billing by the second/minute so create-and-destroy cycles cost actual elapsed usage and the billing-hour reuse pool is unnecessary for it. Hetzner remains supported but not lead; its hourly billing still uses a billing-hour-aware reuse pool — an idle recently-created node within its paid window is reused instead of delete-and-recreate, reaped before crossing into a new paid hour (keep-warm 59 min for Hetzner), the larger benefit being latency from skipping create/boot/install.|] High Minimum Zero [cloud digital-ocean hetzner cloudflare])) (iwbt ([(Technology (Software (Engineering Architecture))) (Technology (Software (Operations ConfigurationManagement)))] Decision [Cluster configuration and Horizon should carry the public-domain mapping for ordinary DNS fallback: criome.net is assigned per cluster, with goldragon owning goldragon.criome.net; the exact NOTA shape is open, but the data belongs in cluster config rather than being hardcoded downstream.] Medium Minimum Zero [horizon cluster-data domain-criome])) (1vj5 ([(Technology (Software (Engineering Architecture)))] Constraint [For the CriomOS-home dictation/desktop-audio path, keep a reliable laptop-microphone fallback and avoid a hard DJI hot-loop dependency: prefer the connected DJI Bluetooth microphone through system audio default-source policy rather than a Whisrs-specific wrapper, and reduce/delete brittle DJI/PipeWire policy rather than adding keepalive code. A DJI keep-alive may exist only as a sidecar consumer of the real DJI mic source, keeping it awake without becoming the selected source; do not let the fix grow into special-case code.] Medium Minimum Zero [criomos-home dji-mic whisrs pipewire])) (p675 ([(Technology (Software (Engineering Architecture)))] Clarification [|The recording system data flow goes from the psyche's laptop microphone, across the network, to the large-ai-node where the always-on capture buffer and real-time multi-modal inference live. The laptop is the audio origin; the large-ai-node is the processing host. The architecture in /1 (recording-system design) implicitly assumed the audio source and processor were the same machine; refine to make the laptop-to-large-ai-node hop explicit.|] Medium Minimum Zero [recording-system large-ai-node])) (qr5o ([(Technology (Software (Engineering Architecture)))] Principle [The closed Domain taxonomy is the broad-routing layer only; fine-grained specificity belongs to the open referent layer of named particulars and to free-text description keywords for narrow concepts, not to deepening the closed enum. A taxonomy layer or leaf earns its place only when it disambiguates and carries real routing load; over-specified leaves that function as referents or keywords are cut. Applied now: the Technology Software subtree is coarsened to curated broad-field leaves under terminal-able sub-domains.] Medium Minimum Zero [spirit domain-taxonomy referent keyword])) (qerc ([(Technology (Software (Engineering Architecture)))] Decision [|Canonical three-part vocabulary: SCHEMA is the specification part. SIGNAL is the movement (transport). SEMA is the body (data at rest, state). Schema specifies both signal and sema; signal carries movement across channels; sema holds the body at rest. This closes the loop between specification, transport, and state.|] High Minimum Zero [schema signal sema-engine])) (hvfe ([(Technology (Software (Engineering Architecture)))] Decision [Manifest the recurring architecture patterns across active worktrees, primary skills, and workspace intent: async mail flow, mail-system actor objects, object-oriented Rust methods on schema-generated types, and related repeated implementation disciplines should be durable instructions rather than only report-local notes.] Medium Minimum Zero [mail-flow schema-generated-types])) (en7k ([(Technology (Software (Engineering Architecture)))] Clarification [Splitting SEMA out of the daemon is only a distant-future consideration if the database must become larger and more available; it is not the current per-plane-crate design and should not be emphasized in a way that confuses agents.] Medium Minimum Zero [sema-engine daemon])) (tw81 ([(Technology (Software (Engineering Architecture)))] Correction [|The Spirit short identifier (returned by the tool and cited in chat) is the shortest-unique base36-lowercase prefix with no collision, minimum FOUR characters (about four to seven), not three — refining the prior minimum-three scheme.|] High Minimum Zero [spirit short-identifier])) (sqnx ([(Technology (Software (Engineering Architecture)))] Clarification